postcontent:
NEED TO SELL THIS WEEKEND.  THIS IS MY BOTTOM DOLLAR.  ITEM WILL BE WITHDRAWN TUESDAY AFTERNOON IF NOT SOLD BY THEN.

The Remington 1100 Tactical 2 is, arguably, one of the finest combat shotguns ever made. I researched it thoroughly before purchasing this. It is more reliable than a Saiga and more durable than a Mossberg. Short 18" barrel with a 6+1 capacity, and you can reload between shots without needing to change magazines. Being gas-operated with a steel receiver it is one of the lightest recoiling 12 gauge shotguns ever made, and it blows fist sized holes in things as fast as you can pull the trigger. This is a very well thought out design.

The following improvements to the TAC2 platform have been made:
*Mesa Tactical Urbano stock with adjustable cheek riser and Limbsaver recoil pad.
*Mesa Tactical 6-round side saddle with Picatinny rail if you want to mount an optic.
*Nordic Components charging handle.
*Nordic Components mag clamp (a mini-rail can be ordered for $17 to mount a flashlight on said clamp).
*Oversized safety installed by Bowers Tactical, who also polished the bolt release.
*Condor Tactical shotgun scabbard with gear pouch.
*Assorted small parts & cleaning kit.
*Manual & warranty card.

VERY LOW ROUND COUNT, mostly Federal birdshot, approximately 300 rds. This is an outstanding shotgun, but just not the right choice for me. Due to an injury I have difficulty handling an 8 pound assault weapon without a sling.

I was going to order the mini-tac rail for the mag clamp (part # TRL-BCT-150) to mount a flashlight and a Tru-Glo fiberoptic front sight, but never got around to it. I highly recommend these items to the new owner. A red dot or holographic sight can be mounted on the top rail, or you can remove it and mount ghost rings. Many possible options.

AMMUNITION INCLUDED: 6 unopened boxes of Winchester #1 Buck, 6 unopened boxes of Winchester Mil-Spec 00 Buck, and a pair of A-Zoom snap caps. That is 60 rounds of the BEST buckshot available, plus a pair of training rounds to practice reloads and dry fire.

title: For Sale:  Denver Shooting Club
postcontent:
Several weeks ago I posted an ad titled "Denver Shooting Club, thoughts?". The response I got was very positive, a lot of Metro area shooters would love to get together for shooting/hunting times and commute when possible to areas like Pawnee in the northeast or Commanche in the south. The next step was to find a proper method of delivery for a shooting club, with a forum being the most obvious answer.
Facebook groups seemed to be a pretty good idea, but with the shift to Timeline it would be tough to keep the group "private", and prevent strangers from seeing your pictures and whatnot, so I decided to use a private forum website, Forumotion.com

Here is the link to what I have created.
http://denvershootingclub.forumotion.com

It really is nothing fancy, take a minute or two to see what it is all about and hopefully it is something to add to favorites and check now and again to see what is going on. I know it may not catch on, but it would be cool to save some gas or money, as well as meet new friends, by commuting to outdoors areas.

Thanks again for reading this, and look up my previous Denver Shooting Club ad if you want to see how this all started. Hopefully I will see you guys on the forum, and in the field.
-Mark

title: For Sale:  Spanish FR-8 308 Very hard to find
postcontent: The FR7 and FR8 were introduced in the 1950s when the Spanish military was already implementing the CETME automatic rifle, but did not yet have sufficient inventory to equip and train all troops. The rifles were made from existing stockpiles of Mauser bolt-action rifles, the FR-7 from the rifle model 1919 Santa Barbara and the FR-8 from the 1943 Santa Barbara carbine. They were adjusted to the new NATO calibre 7.62×51mm and, being of a suitably compact built, the FR 8 was used well into the 1970s by mounted Guardia Civil units in the Sierra Nevada.  The flash hider was designed to be compatible with NATO-standard rifle grenades. The under-barrel tube, which resembles the gas cylinder found on automatic weapons, actually serves as the bayonet mount and as storage for cleaning gear. The rear sight is an elevation-adjustable rotary type with aperatures for 200 m (220 yd), 300 m (330 yd) and 400 m (440 yd), as well as an open "V" notch for 100 metres (110 yd). The front sight is elevation-adjustable via a special tool. Operation is identical to the standard Mauser design.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Conceal carry pistol or deer hunting rifle
postcontent:
I'm looking to trade my Hitachi C10FS 10-Inch Dual Slide Compound Miter Saw for a conceal carry pistol or hunting firearm.  Saw sells for $399

Think of the Hitachi C10FS as the Clydesdale of all the industry's sliding compound miter saw workhorses. It's tough, well built, and feature packed. One of the few saws on the market that bevels to both sides, the Hitachi lets you make compound cuts to the right or left without the hassle of transferring marks or repositioning stock--and the 10 amp motor is situated above the arbor to allow a wider cutting range. Unlike other top-heavy saws, the Hitachi remains well balanced and easy to maneuver--which, along with its smooth-operating blade guard, makes it a relatively safe saw to use. The saw's table allows a good miter range, swinging 57 degrees right and 46 degrees left, and the unique bevel and miter scale makes cutting crown molding a snap whether you're an expert or a novice.
We especially like how Hitachi's multi-V-belt soft-start transfer delivers power smoothly. The saw doesn't jump or buck on start-up, so cuts are generally safe and easy to keep true. The saw cuts 3-1/2- to 12-inch stock at a 90-degree miter, and at 45 degrees the saw handles a 9-inch cut. We also like that the Hitachi features adjustable plastic fences that give support when cutting small pieces close to the blade, but are a bit disappointed that the saw lacks a detent override, a mechanism that disengages the preset table settings and makes it easier to lock into angles close to 0 and 45 degrees.

No question about it, though, the Hitachi C10FS is a tough saw that easily stands up to the rigorous demands of the job site; ours survived a tailgate tumble with hardly a scratch. The well-designed bevel-locks and scales, nicely balanced head, and smooth operation make this a great tool whether you're a professional or a serious home improvement enthusiast. --Mark McDonald

From the Manufacturer
Reduce noise and recoil during start-up with the soft-start feature on this 10-inch saw. The saw is capable of cutting up to 4 by 4 inches at 45 and 90 degrees with a crosscut reach of 12 inches. The electronic speed control helps maintain rpm for constant cutting speed, and you'll get superior accuracy from the linear ball bearing slide system. Professionals will appreciate the right and left bevel cutting capacity and cutting-depth stopper for creating smooth grooves. Your saw purchase includes a slide fence, vise assembly, dust bag

title: For Sale:  Cut Springfield Model 1873 / 1884 in .45-70
location: Between Wetumpka, Alex City, and Clanton ..., Montgomery, Alabama
postcontent:
Shortened Springfield Model 1873 / 1884 in .45-40.  It left the factory as a rifle, and was later cut down to carbine specs.  The serial number matches to an 1886 manufacture, and the Buffington sight, and grooved trigger match to 1884 specs, - but the breech-block is marked 1873.  With the exception of an incorrect to the era ramp-style front sight, and perhaps the absence of a saddle ring and bar, it otherwise appears to be a carbine until closer observation.  The bore on this rifle is minty crisp.  I have only shot one box of 20 rounds through it since I bought it.  I also have 5 boxes of PMC 405 gr. Lead Flat Point, and 1 box of Remington 405 gr. SP that I will sell with the rifle for an additional $150.00 to make a $700.00 package deal.

The gun is fun to shoot, is accurate, and qualifies for use as a "primitive" firearm when hunting in Mississippi.  This gun is also an antique and does not have to transfer through a FFL.  

... I really kind of hate to sell it, but I need to generate some cash to put into some house repairs.  I'm not interested in any trades at this time.  The gun is for sale locally, and I will meet in the middle anywhere between Birmingham, Montgomery, and Auburn, Alabama, - beyond that, the buyer will pay all shipping fees.
